snippet.textDisplay: It's interesting that we still use blue screen for non-film shoots (ex: Avengers). My understanding is that blue was chosen because blue pigment molecules were larger than red and green and produced a sharper mask because their luma representation is the most accurate. In digital, green is (usually) represented by twice as many photosites as blue or red and carries all of the luma data. Yet old-school DPs still use blue. Arri is bayered, so likely has double green photosites.
snippet.textOriginal: It's interesting that we still use blue screen for non-film shoots (ex: Avengers). My understanding is that blue was chosen because blue pigment molecules were larger than red and green and produced a sharper mask because their luma representation is the most accurate. In digital, *green* is (usually) represented by twice as many photosites as blue or red and carries all of the luma data. Yet old-school DPs still use blue. Arri is bayered, so likely has double green photosites.

snippet.textDisplay: Should be noted that almost all the backgrounds of Hoth with the AT-AT are backdrop paintings done primarily by Michael Pangrazio. There was also only 3 paintings of Tatooine  used in the film but they would flip the matte or reverse the image or just use a section of the matte. Example: The Matte used for the famous shot of the Star destroyer flying overhead chasing the Blockade runner was used in the very next shot. The just zoomed in, tilted the camera a bout 20 degrees and matted out the large moon.
